english:
  title: 'Stele Inscription for the Spirit Road of King Taejong of Joseon: Respectfully Composed and Presented with Preface'
  author: Byeon Gyeyangnak
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Heaven is about to bestow great responsibilities upon the virtuous, it must first bring forth sage sons and brilliant grandsons to open the luminous age and extend the grand blessings. Our Joseon's Grand Progenitor Kangheondaewang arose with our Taejong as his son and our present sovereign as his grandson. Alas, what magnificence! How could this be achieved by human effort alone? It is the work of Heaven. Is it not the same as the successive emergence of virtuous and sage rulers in the Shang dynasty, or the transmission through Daeking, Wangki, Munwang, and Muwang of the Zhou? The records of the Yuanzong show that the Lee clan of Jeonju is a house of renown. The Sagong, whose posthumous name was Han, served Silla and married a woman of the Jongseong. Six generations later came one named Geunghyu, who first served Goryeo. Thirteen generations later came the Muwang, the great-great-grandfather of our Taejong, who entered service under the Yuan court as a commander of a thousand men. Four generations successive held their positions with honor and distinction. When Yuan's governance declined, our Hwanwang returned to serve Goryeong's King Gonmin, accumulating merit and virtue whose lineage runs deep.
    Our Sinui Wangtaihou gave birth to Taejong on the eleventh day of the fifth month of the Jeongmi year of Zhizheng at Huzhou in Hamheung. He was the fifth son of our Taejo. Born with extraordinary marks, as he grew his brilliance surpassed all. He loved reading, and his learning advanced daily. Before reaching twenty, he passed the civil examinations of Goryeo. At that time, government was in chaos, the people were scattered, and the nation's fate hung in balance. With a heart moved by compassion for the world, he stood out among his brothers in Taejo's affection. Once, as a document official alongside Attendant-in-Waiting Lee Saek, he journeyed to the Ming court, and through successive promotions rose to the position of Deputy Minister of the Secret Chancellery.
    In the ninth month of the Sinmi year of Hongwu, the Sinui Wangtaihou passed away. Taejong built a mourning hut beside her tomb, intending to complete the three-year mourning period. In spring of the following year, Taejo fell ill during a western journey and returned. Coming to minister with medicines and care, the ministers of Gongyangwang seized this moment to conspire against Taejo with desperate urgency. Taejong read the signs, suppressed the disturbance, eliminated the conspirators, and all schemes dissolved. In the seventh month of autumn, together with the generals and ministers, he proclaimed righteous doctrine, enthroned Taejo, transformed the house into a kingdom, and was invested as Lord of Jeongan.
    In the summer of the Gapsu year, the High Emperor of Ming ordered the sending of a son to pay court. Since Taejo recognized that Taejong possessed mastery of the Classics and propriety, standing supreme among his sons, he sent him at once to fulfill the command. Upon arriving, Taejong's exposition met the Emperor's approval, he was shown great courtesy, and granted passage home with gifts. In the eighth month of autumn of the Mugin year, Taejo fell gravely ill. Power-seeking ministers gathered their factions, some hoping to seize regency over a young prince and fulfill their ambitions. The danger became imminent. Taejong discerned the situation and swiftly eliminated the conspirators. At that time, relatives and ministers all wished to petition for Taejong's investiture as crown prince, but he steadfastly declined, instead recommending and elevating Gongjong. Upon petition to Taejo, Gongjong was invested as crown prince to stabilize the state.
    On the jeongchuk day of the ninth month, as Taejo's illness did not improve, he abdicated to Gongjong. In the first month of the Gyeongchen year of Jianwen, rebel Park Po plotted to murder his brother, secretly inducing the father and son Bang Gan to raise arms in rebellion. Taejong commanded his armies and quelled the disturbance, executing Park Po but releasing the others, merely exiling Bang Gan without severing familial bonds. Since Gongjong had no heir and the works of founding the kingdom and stabilizing the state were all Taejong's achievements, he was invested as crown prince. In the eleventh month, Gongjong also transmitted his position to Taejong due to illness, dispatching an envoy to seek the Emperor's mandate.
    In the sixth month of the following Sinsa year, the Jianwen Emperor sent the Eunuch Zhang Gin and others, bearing imperial decrees and seals, to invest Taejong as King. In winter, the Imperial Secretariat sent Pan Wenkui to present royal robes, his rank equivalent to that of a consort king. When the current Emperor ascended the throne in the Imopny year, the left chancellor Heun came to congratulate the enthronement, and the Emperor praised his loyalty. In the following Gyemi year of the fourth month, imperial decrees and seals were bestowed, dispatched officials confirmed him as king with renewed honors, and in autumn, the Hanlin official Wang Yenryeng arrived with the nine-emblem dragon robes and gifts of silk and books—Taejo receiving silk and books, the Wonkyeong Wangtaihou receiving crowns, robes, and silk, each according to rank. From this time onward, the Emperor's gifts continued without ceasing year after year.
    In the Eulyu year, because Hanyang was the capital chosen by Taejo, he dismissed the objections of his ministers and relocated there. In the Jeonghai year, the Emperor spoke to envoys attending the New Year audience, saying: "The King of Joseon serves the great with utmost sincerity." Thereafter, whenever envoys arrived, the Emperor repeatedly praised this sincerity. In the fifth month of the Muja year, Taejo passed away. Taejong's grief knew no bounds. He dwelt in the mourning chamber, conducting the funeral and burial according to propriety. Dispatching an envoy to report the death, the Emperor was deeply grieved and suspended court business. He sent officials from the Ministry of Rites to offer sacrificial offerings and posthumously honored him as Kangheun. Furthermore, through imperial decree, Taejong was granted substantial funeral gifts.
    In the winter of the Imjin year, a report came that descendants of the Wang family had been living secretly among the common people. The officials requested their execution. Taejong declared: "The rise of emperors follows Heaven's Mandate. The elimination of Wang descendants contradicts Taejo's original intention." He thereupon issued an edict: "Surviving descendants of the Wang family shall be permitted to settle peacefully in their occupations." In the sixth month of the Gapja year, sweet dew descended upon Weolkwang district of Hamheung and Baekun Mountain of Jeongpyeong. The following month of the Eulmi year, sweet dew again descended on Deoksan Valley of Hamheung—phenomena unprecedented in our Eastern realm. Officials jointly submitted memorials of congratulation, but the king did not accept them.
    In the sixth month of the Musul year, the crown prince Jae was found derelict in virtue and was deposed, invested as Lord of Yangnyeong. Our present sovereign, being sagacious, filial, fraternal, and devoted to learning without ceasing, was favored by the people and invested as crown prince with report to the Emperor. The Emperor granted approval. In the eighth month of this year, he abdicated in favor of our sovereign. An envoy was dispatched to seek the Emperor's mandate. In the eleventh month, our sovereign received the imperial seal and charter, taking the title Sungdeok Singong Sangwang. In the first month of the following Gihai year, the Emperor dispatched Liu Chuan from the Imperial Secretariat bearing imperial decree to invest our sovereign as King.
    In the fifth month, the Japanese of Tsushima Island invaded the border, killing and pillaging soldiers. The Premier and ministers were commanded to lead a naval force to suppress them, and the Tsushima Japanese submitted as before. In the eighth month, the Emperor sent an envoy bearing gifts and a feast. The imperial edict read approximately: "Your Majesty's sincerity is resolute, your devotion to the court unceasing, your virtue and intent singular and steadfast, enabling you to discern the worthy and elevate the virtuous, ensuring the continuation of ancestral sacrifices and fulfilling the hopes of your people." Gifts and a feast were also bestowed upon our sovereign, with the edict reading: "Your father's steadfast maturity in respecting the Way of Heaven shows a loyalty and submissiveness that only deepens with time."
    In the ninth month, King Gongjong passed away. Our sovereign observed the mourning rites of severed hemp and month-counting observance, dispatching an envoy to report the death. In the following fourth month, the Emperor sent an envoy to offer sacrifices and bestowed the posthumous title Gongjong. In spring of this year, our sovereign led the ministers in requesting the title of Taisang Wang, but this was not approved. In the seventh month of autumn, the Wonkyeong Wangtaihou passed away. When our sovereign's grief exceeded propriety, the Emperor decreed he follow the shortened mourning period, but the sovereign insisted on the longer observance, maintaining white garments throughout. On the imjon day of the ninth month, the Wangtaihou was buried on Daeomosan of Gwangju, and the tomb was named Hyeonnreung.
    In the giuchuk year's ninth month, our sovereign received the imperial seal and charter, elevated his father to the title Taisang Wang. In the tenth month, following Taejong's direction, the eldest son Hyang was invested as crown prince. Taejong possessed uncommon virtue, illuminated the learning of sages, his filial piety and fraternity extended to the spiritual realm, his sincerity and reverence rectified the ancestral temples and state shrines. In serving the great, the Son of Heaven praised his sincerity; in diplomatic relations, the Japanese nation acknowledged his righteous way. He revered Heaven and pitied the people, honored frugality and controlled expenditure, prioritized virtue and propriety while being circumspect in punishment, elevated the loyal and direct while dismissing the treacherous, opposed heterodoxy and prohibited illicit worship, harmonized ancient and modern in establishing institutions, illuminated civil teachings and strengthened military preparations. All accumulated abuses were reformed and every endeavor flourished. The four quarters found peace, the people enjoyed security, and all things prospered. The Way of the Emperor had reached its apex. Thus it was fitting that he received the Emperor's profound favor and twice witnessed the auspicious sign of sweet dew descending.
    In the fourth month of the Imyin year, Taejong first fell ill. In the fifth month on the byeongyin day, he passed away at the Lodge. Our sovereign could not bear his grief—for three days he ate nothing. The ministers wept and implored him to take nourishment, but he refused entirely. He established a three-year mourning period, not observing the shortened observance. Taejong was fifty-six years of age, having reigned nineteen years, dwelling peacefully in retirement for five years. Suddenly the bow and sword were left behind. Great and small officials, down to servants and slaves, all wailed in endless sorrow. As time passed, the grief only deepened, as though they mourned their own parents. Alas, such anguish!
    On the sixth day of the ninth month of this year, the gapja day, he was interred jointly with the Wonkyeong Wangtaihou at her tomb, fulfilling his dying wish. When news of his death reached the court, the Emperor was greatly grieved and suspended all business. He specially dispatched Yang Seon and other officials from the Ministry of Rites to offer sacrifices. The text of the sacrificial offering read approximately: "The King was steadfast and sincere, sagacious and accomplished, reverently serving the court with unfailing loyalty and submissiveness. The distant news of his passing deeply moves our sorrow." Imperial decrees were issued granting him the posthumous name Gongjong and bestowing generous funerary gifts upon our sovereign. Indeed, through the successive virtues and achievements of our Taejong and the filial sincerity of our sovereign, Heaven's will was fulfilled, and thus at life's end, the honors shown were as complete and manifest as these.
    The Wonkyeong Wangtaihou bore the surname Min of the Yeokheung lineage. Descending from the Mungha Sija Pyeongzhang Saksa, the cultural sage Mungyeongong Lingmo through six generations to the Hwanggogjo Jongryu who served Milyeong, then to the Hwangjzogjo Mun Soonwho served as Panjik Sika, then to the Hwangjjo Dae Gwang Yeokheung Buownjun who served as Dae Gwang Boyokuk Sungnok Daebo, then to the Hwanggo Sunchung Dongdeok Chanwhakongsin Dae Gwang Boyokuk Sungnok Daebo Yeokheung Buownjun Sumunje Daeje Hak Youngye Mun Chunchu Gwansa Sijo Mundohuije. The Hwangbi Songshi was enfeoffed as the Grand Lady of the Three Hans, daughter of the high-ranked Yeokheung nobleman Rimryanggun Yuanxuan. Through accumulated virtue, blessings flowed forth, producing one of remarkable intelligence and wisdom.
    When of marrying age, a suitable match was sought, and she came to wed our Taejong. In his youth, though Taejong harbored ambitions to save the world and devoted himself to the Classics and histories, neglecting household management, the Wangtaihou managed the household with parsimony, attended carefully to domestic provisions to support his studies, instructed their many sons in righteous conduct, and treated the concubines and attendants with propriety, fulfilling the duties of a wife most excellently. In the Imsin year of Hongwu, she was invested as the Princess of Jeongnyeong. In the Mugin year, as Taejong worked to stabilize the realm amid great danger and isolation, the Wangtaihou devoted herself entirely to assisting him in accomplishing this great work. In spring of the Gyeongchen year, she was elevated to Jeongbin; that winter, when Taejong ascended the throne, she was invested as Jeongbi. In the Gyemi year of Yongle, the Emperor bestowed upon her crowns and robes, and from this year until the Jeongyu year, she received imperial gifts five times over.
    In the winter of the Musul year, our sovereign elevated her to the title Housdeok Wangdaebi. In the ninth month of the Gyeongja year, she was posthumously honored as the Wonkyeong Wangtaihou at the age of fifty-six. The Wangtaihou possessed a tranquil, virtuous, chaste, and reverent nature, ably assisting Taejong in managing the inner realm. For twenty years, her conduct in the palace was dignified and harmonious. She bore a sage son to inherit the state shrines and enjoyed the glory of proper retirement. Upon her passing, all attendants and concubines grieved without exception. How perfectly did the wife emulate the mother's role! She bore four sons and four daughters. Our sovereign was the third. The eldest was Jae, the next was Bo, invested as Lord of Hyonjung; the third was Jong, invested as Lord of Seongnyeong, who predeceased her.
    The eldest daughter was Princess Jeongsung, who married the Lord of Cheongpyeong Yi Baekgang—not of the same Yi line. The next was Princess Gyeongjeong, who married the Lord of Pyeongyang Jo Daerim. The next was Princess Gyeongan, who married the Lord of Gilchang Gwon Kyue, but she too predeceased. The last was Princess Jeongsun, who married the Lord of Uisan Nam Hui. The concubine Gwon gave birth to one daughter, Princess Jeong Hui, who married the Lord of Unseong Park Jonguwe. Princess Sohae of the House Rho bore one daughter, still young. Princess Sinnyeong of the House Shin bore three sons and seven daughters. The eldest, named In, was invested as Lord of Gongjung; the rest are young. The eldest daughter was Princess Jeongsin, who married the Lord of Yeongpyeong Yun Gyetong. The next was Princess Jeongjeong, who married the Lord of Hanwon Jo Suon. The next was Princess Sookjeong, who married the Lord of Ilseong Jeong Hyojeon; the rest are young. The maidservant An bore one son and three daughters, all young. Kim bore one son named Bi, invested as Lord of Gyeongnung. Ko bore one son; Choi bore one son and one daughter; Lee bore one son; Kim bore one daughter, all young.
    Our Gongjong Gongbi Shim was the daughter of Mungha Sija Deokbu and his fourth son On. She bore four sons and two daughters, the eldest being the crown prince, the rest young. Yangnyeong married the daughter of Kim Hanno, bearing three sons and one daughter, all young. Hyonjung married the daughter of the former Panjung Gunji Jeong Yi, bearing four sons and one daughter, all young. Seongnung married the daughter of the former Jeolla Provincial Inspector Seong Eok, with no issue. Princess Jeongsung bore one daughter who married the Guard Officer Yi Gyerin of the Dragon Emblem Guard—not of the same Yi line. Princess Gyeongjeong bore four daughters, the eldest marrying the Aide of the Tonnyeong Prefecture An Jin, the next marrying the Junior Scholar Kim Jungeom, the rest young. Princess Gyeongan bore two sons, the eldest named Dam who married the daughter of Hanseong Junior Minister Jeong Yeon, the next young. Princess Jeongssun bore two sons and one daughter, all young. Gyeongnung married the daughter of the Ministry of Households Official Kim Gwan, bearing two sons, both young. Gongjung married the daughter of the Ministry of War Official Choi Sakang, bearing two daughters, both young.
    Your subject has observed that our Taejong's great virtue and sublime achievement already stand supreme among all the monarchs of history. Yet his consort's wisdom and her contribution to the inner realm can be compared to the harmony between the sagewoman and the sages of old, their beauty equal. The assembled ministers all desire to carve an inscription upon the spirit road stele of the mausoleum to illuminate eternally for future generations. Our sovereign has commanded your subject to undertake this task. Your subject, receiving this command with reverence and trepidation, dares not refuse. Respectfully bowing and presenting this inscription:
    Heaven watches over our eastern land,
    Bestowing upon us our Taejong.
    With constant diligence Taejong labored,
    Great virtue dwelling in his person.
    He upheld his sage father's throne,
    Accomplishing grand merit thereby,
    Approaching the imperial court,
    Speaking with quiet composure.
    Receiving the Emperor's grace abundantly,
    He preserved our people secure.
    Reading portents, quelling rebellion,
    Honoring the elder brother's succession.
    Though family strife arose,
    Fraternal love remained deep.
    The perfection of filial duty
    Seldom heard in ages past.
    His virtue was profound and thick,
    His merit magnificent and great,
    Heaven's gaze shone clear upon him,
    Bestowing protection anew.
    The brilliant golden seals gleamed
    Shining both before and after.
    Imperial decrees arrived in succession,
    He received the dragon throne.
    Following ancestral instruction,
    He returned to Han's northern lands.
    Creating ritual and music,
    They bloomed in splendid profusion.
    Dwelling in mourning at the tomb,
    His grief knew no limit.
    In burial and in sacrifice,
    He followed the ancient forms.
    Serving the court with reverence,
    The Emperor praised his sincerity.
    With solemn conduct of the rites,
    He moved the spiritual realm.
    In relations with neighboring lands,
    The Japanese kingdom bowed.
    He sheltered the Wang's descendants,
    Permitting them peaceful livelihood.
    Within and without, peace reigned,
    For twenty years enduring.
    Sweet dew gently falling
    Descended year upon Hamheung.
    Casting out the unworthy son,
    Elevating virtue for the throne,
    He hoped for endless years,
    His father ruling this earth below.
    Yet why did fate's swift passage come?
    One illness beyond remedy.
    Alas, the virtuous son,
    His sorrow knew no bounds.
    For three days he ate nothing,
    His grief could not be contained.
    In all the ceremonies of mourning,
    He followed ritual's prescribed course.
    The Emperor hearing grew sorrowful,
    Sent envoys bearing sacrifice.
    Bestowing grand posthumous honor,
    Granting generous funerary gifts,
    The completeness of state honors,
    Filled his servants' hearts with joy.
    His consort matched him in virtue,
    Most truly harmonious and serene.
    Quietly aiding to secure the realm,
    Matching great wisdom with her grace.
    She bore a sage son most wise,
    To inherit the ancestral shrine.
    Like heaven, firm and luminous,
    Such was Gongjong's virtue,
    Like earth, deep and yielding,
    Such was Wonkyeong's way.
    In life like lute and zither friends,
    In death together in one tomb.
    The descendants flourishing forth,
    Alas, like the auspicious qilin.
    The ancestral sacrifices continue,
    For ten thousand times ten thousand springs.
    Your subject respectfully presents these words,
    Carved upon the jade of stone,
    Unwearing through endless ages,
    Illuminating our eastern realm.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Wonkyeong Wangtaihou refers to Queen Min, the principal consort of King Taejong, who was posthumously honored with this title.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'sweet dew' (ganroj) descending on Hamheung and other locations during Taejong's reign was interpreted as a heavenly portent signifying the virtue of the ruler.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Sagewoman of Shu and the sages' alludes to exemplary women of ancient China whose wisdom matched that of great sages.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Tsushima Island'' refers to the Japanese island that frequently sent pirate raids (wakō) against Korean shores during this period.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'dragon throne' and dragon-related imagery throughout represent imperial or royal authority and legitimacy.
